{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537747"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:20:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:20:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16064"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16064"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.02,0.78,0.05,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8755"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8755"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"145"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4453"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40154"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is in active labour with her second child at 39 weeks gestation. She has gestational diabetes managed with metformin. Her first child weighed 4.2 kg at birth. She has no other significant medical history and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The fetal heart rate is 145/min with good variability. After delivery of the fetal head, there is retraction of the head against the perineum and the anterior shoulder fails to deliver with the next contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Zavanelli manoeuvre","Emergency caesarean section","McRoberts manoeuvre","Fundal pressure","Immediate episiotomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with shoulder dystocia, an obstetric emergency where the anterior shoulder becomes impacted behind the maternal pubic symphysis after delivery of the fetal head. Risk factors present in this case include gestational diabetes and previous macrosomic baby. The turtle sign of the head retracting against perineum is pathognomonic. The mnemonic HELPERR may assist in remembering the steps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EH - call for Help.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EE - evaluate for Episiotomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EL - legs (the McRoberts manouevre)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EP - Suprapubic Pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EE - Enter manoueuvres (internal rotation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ER - Remove the posterior arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ER - Roll the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMcRoberts manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line management for shoulder dystocia. It involves sharp flexion of the maternal thighs against the abdomen, which straightens the sacrum relative to the lumbar spine and rotates the pubic symphysis cephalad. This manoeuvre alone resolves approximately 40% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFundal pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in shoulder dystocia as it can worsen the impaction and increase the risk of brachial plexus injury. It may also cause uterine rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is not possible once the fetal head is delivered. The baby must be delivered vaginally at this point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZavanelli manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E (cephalic replacement) is a last resort procedure with significant risks. It should only be considered after other manoeuvres have failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate episiotomy\u003C/strong\u003E alone does not resolve shoulder dystocia as the obstruction occurs at the level of the bony pelvis. While an episiotomy may be needed to facilitate internal manoeuvres, it should not be performed until these manoeuvres are required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf McRoberts manoeuvre fails, subsequent steps include suprapubic pressure, internal rotation manoeuvres (Woods\u0027 screw, reverse Woods\u0027 screw), delivery of the posterior arm, and finally more desperate measures such as intentional clavicular fracture or the Zavanelli manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Shoulder dystocia is an obstetric emergency requiring immediate recognition and systematic management using the HELPERR mnemonic.","Risk factors for shoulder dystocia include maternal diabetes, previous shoulder dystocia, and fetal macrosomia.","The turtle sign (head retracting against perineum) is the key clinical indicator of shoulder dystocia."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG). Shoulder dystocia: Green-top guideline no. 42 [Internet]. 2nd ed. London: RCOG; 2012 [cited 2024 Nov 22]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/media/ewgpnmio/gtg_42.pdf","Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Diagnosis and management of suspected fetal macrosomia [Internet]. East Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2024 Nov 22]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Diagnosis-Management-Suspected-Fetal-Macrosomia.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90291"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16064"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90291"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-04T07:55:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T07:55:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8755"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107875"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel